research/history/round_summaries/round_0048.json:105:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `gated` family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `K`. It follows the current mainline logic because the baseline, LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess questions have already been resolved on this recipe, and the recent K sweep has now shown successful transfer at `K=96`, `K=64`, and `K=32`. The main risk is that `K=24` may fall outside the regime where the improved gating recipe remains effective, but that is exactly the highest-value remaining single-variable question for mapping the LUTurbo cost-quality boundary.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0179.json:52:      "This matched probe stays inside the likely feasible encoder-cost regime and is more informative than another routed/bucketed-style over-budget probe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Rounds 92 through 94 suggest the soft-codebook coarse branch is the first recent non-mainline idea with real signal, but the cheaper single-stage selectors (`lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`, `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual`, `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual`) still did not beat the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor. The single most informative remaining matched architecture probe is `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`: it keeps the same LUTurbo-compatible static-library export path, but asks whether a front-loaded sparse budget after codebook projection can preserve most of the quality while shifting more of the work into the earlier coarse correction and reducing reliance on a large second-stage cleanup. This round answers one question only: under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, is that asymmetric soft-codebook two-stage architecture intrinsically worth any future follow-up, or should the soft-codebook branch be treated as unable to justify more complexity than the current mainline?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays within the round policy: one probe, one primary variable, allowed `K`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` is explicit. I am choosing the asymmetric soft-codebook two-stage variant over routed, whitened, or bucketed alternatives because it is the simplest remaining probe that still targets LUTurbo-relevant execution structure rather than adding extra selector or preprocessing machinery. The main risk is that it still inherits more moving parts than the mainline, so only a clearly strong curve would justify keeping this branch alive.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:77:    "self_review": "This stays within the round policy: one probe, one primary variable, allowed `K`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` is explicit. I am choosing the asymmetric soft-codebook two-stage variant over routed, whitened, or bucketed alternatives because it is the simplest remaining probe that still targets LUTurbo-relevant execution structure rather than adding extra selector or preprocessing machinery. The main risk is that it still inherits more moving parts than the mainline, so only a clearly strong curve would justify keeping this branch alive.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0043.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0043.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 42 answered the loss question cleanly: removing the auxiliary term produced an almost identical curve shape and a slightly worse endpoint than the `gated+signum+LR=2.0e-3` anchor, so the loss branch does not look promising. The next single question in the prescribed order is therefore preprocess: with the strengthened `gated` mainline recipe fixed at `K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=2.0e-3`, does enabling Hadamard preprocessing improve conditioning enough to lower the full training curve, or is the plain input path still best?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0043.json:20:    "summary": "Stay on the active `gated` family and restore the current anchor recipe at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, with the same runtime knobs pinned, and change only the preprocess variable by enabling `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Judge this round by the whole trajectory, not just terminal FVU: if Hadamard conditioning makes early and mid training smoother and finishes below the current `0.148156` anchor, keep preprocess live; if it is neutral or worse again, close the preprocess branch and then move on to K mapping.",
