research/history/round_summaries/round_0085.json:19:    "hypothesis": "With `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` clearly weaker than the current `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor, the next and only justified matched architecture probe is `lowrank_residual_vq`. It preserves the same low-rank coarse-trunk intuition and static-library export contract while swapping staged residual selection for a harder discrete coarse assignment. If that discrete variant cannot materially challenge the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` anchor under the exact same `K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=2.0e-3` recipe, then hard residual-VQ is not worth continuing in the current LUTurbo-aligned regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:19:    "hypothesis": "The `gated` family may only be competitive at the largest support, so stepping `K` down from `128` to `96` while holding `EF=12`, `optimizer=signum`, and `lr=1.6e-3` tests one question only: does `gated` remain competitive on the adjacent frontier point, or is its apparent edge confined to `K=128`?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:20:    "summary": "Round 35 answered the preprocess probe: Hadamard did not improve the anchored `gated` recipe, leaving no meaningful recipe knobs unexplored in the prescribed order. The next single-variable move is therefore `K`. Use the plain `gated` anchor and drop only `K` to `96`. This is the highest-value neighboring check because there is already a strong `topk` control at `K=96` (`0.171856`), so the run directly tells us whether `gated` has broader family viability or whether it should be treated as a narrow `K=128` specialization. Read the curve shape as well as the endpoint: if `gated@96` is smooth and beats or matches the `topk@96` control comfortably, keep the family alive across K; if it is clearly worse or unstable, treat `gated` as exhausted outside the single `K=128` point.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:25:    "self_review": "This keeps the same family, preserves EF at 12, changes exactly one primary variable (`K`), and only moves K after the LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess probes failed to improve the anchored recipe. Choosing `K=96` minimizes extrapolation because it is adjacent to the current gated anchor and has a matched topk frontier point for direct comparison.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:30:        "value": "gated"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:51:      "Round 36 begins the first K probe for gated after recipe tuning was exhausted: gated, K=96, EF=12, signum, LR=1.6e-3.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:52:      "Compare gated@96 against the existing topk@96 control and judge curve shape, not just terminal FVU; this determines whether gated generalizes beyond the isolated K=128 win."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:55:      "If `gated@96` is competitive with or better than `topk@96`, gated deserves at least one more K-mapping round within the allowed grid.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:56:      "If `gated@96` clearly trails `topk@96`, stop spending mainline rounds on gated except as the recorded K=128 incumbent."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:67:    "architecture": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:76:    "description": "Round 35 answered the preprocess probe: Hadamard did not improve the anchored `gated` recipe, leaving no meaningful recipe knobs unexplored in the prescribed order. The next single-variable move is therefore `K`. Use the plain `gated` anchor and drop only `K` to `96`. This is the highest-value neighboring check because there is already a strong `topk` control at `K=96` (`0.171856`), so the run directly tells us whether `gated` has broader family viability or whether it should be treated as a narrow `K=128` specialization. Read the curve shape as well as the endpoint: if `gated@96` is smooth and beats or matches the `topk@96` control comfortably, keep the family alive across K; if it is clearly worse or unstable, treat `gated` as exhausted outside the single `K=128` point.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0036.json:77:    "self_review": "This keeps the same family, preserves EF at 12, changes exactly one primary variable (`K`), and only moves K after the LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess probes failed to improve the anchored recipe. Choosing `K=96` minimizes extrapolation because it is adjacent to the current gated anchor and has a matched topk frontier point for direct comparison.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0090.json:19:    "hypothesis": "After the simpler low-rank single-stage selectors (`lowrank_residual`, `lowrank_gated_residual`, `lowrank_jumprelu_residual`, and `lowrank_grouped_residual`) all failed against the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor, the most informative remaining matched architecture probe is `whitened_lowrank_residual`. It keeps the same low-rank trunk and single-stage static-library residual decode, but changes only the residual conditioning before support selection. This answers a clean question: was the mainline gain coming from the second residual stage itself, or can a better-conditioned single-stage selector recover enough quality to be worth any further attention. If `whitened_lowrank_residual` is still clearly weaker under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, then the current evidence favors the two-stage residual mechanism rather than more single-stage low-rank variants.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 56 answered the loss question on the strengthened `gated` recipe cleanly enough: removing the auxiliary term finished essentially flat-to-worse (`0.142968` vs the `0.142923` anchor), so the mainline recipe remains `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. With LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess now all re-checked on the active family, the next single question in the prescribed order is back on the K axis: if we keep the finalized `gated` recipe fixed and reduce only `K` from `128` to `96`, does the lower-cost point still reproduce a healthy full training curve under the now-settled mainline recipe, or was the earlier `K=96` result partly specific to an intermediate recipe-validation phase?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:20:    "summary": "Stay on the active `gated` family and hold the now-settled mainline recipe fixed at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Change only `K` from `128` to `96` to refresh the first lower-cost deployment point under the finalized recipe. Judge this run by the whole trajectory, not just terminal FVU: if the curve remains smooth and lands near or below the current `gated@96` frontier (`0.160940`), then the strengthened recipe is stable enough to treat that lower-cost point as a reliable LUTurbo candidate; if it degrades materially, re-open the question of whether the prior K sweep depended on transient recipe-state rather than the settled mainline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:30:        "value": "gated"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:79:      "Round 56 showed that on the Hadamard-enabled `gated@128` anchor, removing the auxiliary loss is neutral-to-slightly-worse (`0.142968` vs `0.142923`), so `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` should remain part of the strengthened mainline recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:80:      "Round 57 returns to the K axis under the now-settled `gated` recipe by rechecking `K=96` at fixed `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`, and `EF=12`, with emphasis on whether the full curve remains clean and deployment-relevant."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:83:      "If the refreshed `gated@96` run reproduces a healthy curve near or better than the existing `0.160940` point, treat the lower-cost frontier as stable and continue down the K ladder only if a further deployment question remains.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:84:      "If `gated@96` degrades materially relative to its existing frontier point, investigate whether the earlier K sweep was less stable than it appeared before making more low-K conclusions."
