research/history/round_summaries/round_0046.json:95:    "architecture": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0046.json:104:    "description": "Continue the active `gated` mainline and keep the improved recipe fixed: `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Change only `K` from `96` to `64` to test whether the new recipe yields a stronger lower-cost deployment point at the next allowed support level. Judge the run by the full trajectory as well as the endpoint: if it stays smooth and finishes materially below the old `gated@64` control (`0.195828`), the improved recipe is genuinely useful beyond the `K=128` anchor; if it falls back toward the old curve, treat the current gain as mainly a high-K effect.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:19:    "hypothesis": "After the plain, gated, JumpReLU, grouped, whitened, and factorized single-stage low-rank residual families all failed to challenge the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor, the most informative remaining matched architecture probe is `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`. It preserves LUTurbo-compatible static-library export, but tests a different decomposition hypothesis: a coarse static codebook projection followed by one sparse residual correction may recover some of the mainline's quality without requiring a full second sparse residual stage. If this codebook-assisted single-stage family is still clearly weaker under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, then the current evidence favors true two-stage residual allocation over coarse-codebook-plus-single-stage alternatives.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:19:    "hypothesis": "With the `gated` mainline stalled for eleven rounds and the lighter selector probes `group_topk` and `bucketed_topk` both coming back clearly worse, the next highest-value matched architecture probe is `codebook_topk`: it remains LUTurbo-compatible because the reconstruction is still a finite sum over static libraries, but it changes the architecture by adding a hard coarse codebook selection before the sparse residual. This round answers one question only: under the matched `K=128`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EF=12` recipe, is `codebook_topk` intrinsically strong enough to justify any later follow-up, or should it be ruled out immediately.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:20:    "summary": "Run one matched architecture probe by switching `ARCHITECTURE` from `gated` to `codebook_topk` while keeping `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:51:      "Round 64 spends the single allowed matched architecture probe on `codebook_topk` after `group_topk` and `bucketed_topk` both failed to beat the matched `gated` control.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:53:      "Judge this probe strictly as a family-worthiness test against matched `gated` K128: if it is clearly worse, discard it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, record the result but still return to the mainline per policy."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:56:      "If `codebook_topk` is clearly worse than matched `gated`, discard the family and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:57:      "If `codebook_topk` is roughly competitive, record it as a possible coarse-plus-residual deployment direction but still return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0064.json:58:      "If `codebook_topk` unexpectedly beats matched `gated`, schedule at most one later follow-up after the mandated return to the `gated` mainline."
