research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 50 answered the `K=8` question positively: the strengthened `gated` recipe (`signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`) continued to transfer downward and now owns the `K=8` frontier with a materially better endpoint than the prior control. The next single question is whether this benefit survives at the extreme support limit: if we keep the same improved recipe fixed and reduce only `K` to `4`, does `gated` still preserve enough quality to remain the best point at the minimum allowed online cost, or does the family advantage finally break at the bottom of the K grid?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:20:    "summary": "Continue the active `gated` mainline and keep the improved recipe fixed: `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Change only `K` from `8` to `4` to test whether the current recipe improvement extends to the minimum allowed support level. Judge the run by the full trajectory as well as the endpoint: if training remains smooth and finishes clearly below the current `K=4` control (`0.462789`), then `gated` has established a full low-K transfer across the entire allowed grid; if the curve degrades sharply or the endpoint lands near or above that control, treat `K=8` as the practical lower bound of the current gated recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `gated` family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `K`. It follows the current mainline logic because the baseline, LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess questions have already been resolved on this recipe, and the recent K sweep has now shown successful transfer at `K=96`, `K=64`, `K=32`, `K=24`, `K=16`, and `K=8`. The main risk is that `K=4` may be beyond the useful regime for the improved gating recipe, but that is exactly the final high-value single-variable question needed to map the LUTurbo cost-quality boundary on the allowed K grid.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:30:        "value": "gated"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:79:      "Round 50 established that the improved `gated` recipe transfers down to `K=8`: it beat the previous `K=8` control and now holds that frontier point.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:83:      "If improved `gated@4` clearly beats the existing `K=4` control with a healthy curve, the current gated recipe has demonstrated full-grid transfer and the next step should return to recipe-level refinement or deployment-oriented interpretation rather than further K descent.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:84:      "If `gated@4` fails to beat the control or shows clearly worse curve shape, stop the downward sweep and treat `K=8` as the lowest strong gated point under the current recipe."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:95:    "architecture": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:104:    "description": "Continue the active `gated` mainline and keep the improved recipe fixed: `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Change only `K` from `8` to `4` to test whether the current recipe improvement extends to the minimum allowed support level. Judge the run by the full trajectory as well as the endpoint: if training remains smooth and finishes clearly below the current `K=4` control (`0.462789`), then `gated` has established a full low-K transfer across the entire allowed grid; if the curve degrades sharply or the endpoint lands near or above that control, treat `K=8` as the practical lower bound of the current gated recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0051.json:105:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `gated` family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `K`. It follows the current mainline logic because the baseline, LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess questions have already been resolved on this recipe, and the recent K sweep has now shown successful transfer at `K=96`, `K=64`, `K=32`, `K=24`, `K=16`, and `K=8`. The main risk is that `K=4` may be beyond the useful regime for the improved gating recipe, but that is exactly the final high-value single-variable question needed to map the LUTurbo cost-quality boundary on the allowed K grid.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:7:  "family_name": "routed",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 60 showed that matched `jumprelu` is competitive enough to avoid immediate dismissal but still clearly trails the strengthened `gated` anchor (`0.148243` vs `0.142923`), so the next single architecture question should test the closest support-selection near-neighbor rather than another looser variant. `routed` preserves LUTurbo's static-vector finite weighted-sum reconstruction contract while separating support routing from activation magnitude, so this round asks one clean yes/no question: under the exact current mainline recipe (`K=128`, `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`), is `routed` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to justify any later follow-up as a deployment-relevant family?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:20:    "summary": "Run one matched architecture probe on `routed`. Keep the current mainline recipe fixed at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`, and the same runtime knobs, and change only `ARCHITECTURE` from `gated` to `routed`. Judge this probe by the whole trajectory, not just the endpoint: if `routed` stays smooth and lands near the `0.142923` `gated` anchor, it is worth keeping in reserve because decoupled routing may offer a better LUTurbo cost/quality tradeoff than full gating; if it is clearly worse across the curve, archive it as a non-promising matched alternative and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:23:    "family_name": "routed",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 61 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the settled mainline recipe fixed. `routed` is the highest-value remaining probe because it stays very close to the successful `gated` family while changing only the support-selection mechanism, which is directly relevant to LUTurbo online cost. The main risk is that the matched `gated`-tuned recipe may not be ideal for routed support, but that is acceptable for a family-worthiness screen.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:30:        "value": "routed"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:79:      "Round 60 showed that matched `jumprelu` is only modestly worse than the strengthened `gated` anchor (`0.148243` vs `0.142923`), so simpler support-shaping variants are still worth probing when mainline progress stalls.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:80:      "`routed` remains LUTurbo-compatible because the reconstruction is still a finite weighted sum over a static decoder library with fixed `K`; the architectural change is confined to using a separate router for support selection while preserving the same export form.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:81:      "Round 61 should judge `routed` purely as a family-worthiness probe against the current `gated@128` anchor: if it is clearly worse or unstable, archive it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, keep exactly one later follow-up slot available."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:84:      "If matched `routed` is clearly worse than the strengthened `gated` anchor, return to the `gated` mainline next round and close this probe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:85:      "If matched `routed` is roughly competitive with a healthy curve, still return to the `gated` mainline next round, but preserve one later revisit because decoupled routing may better align with LUTurbo online-cost goals.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:86:      "If matched `routed` unexpectedly beats the current `gated` anchor, return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy but schedule exactly one later follow-up for this family."
